<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54082d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54082d">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54082d"> 82(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> chain of eyewitnesses / John Polycarp Irenaeus <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54082d"><li>FW 254.09 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kf/lexkf.htm#n54082d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kf/l39kf.htm#n54082d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54082d">MS BL 47477-294</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:439 <a name="kad9" href="../../ff/fdra/kda.htm#kfd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kf/kfd8.htm#n54082d">Draft: II.1&sect;6.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Irenaeus]</font> tells us that he can recall the very place where Polycarp used to sit and teach, his manner of speech, his mode of life, &hellip; his frequent reference to St. John and others who had seen Christ, how he (Polycarp) used to repeat from memory their discourses &hellip; and how he was instructed by those who were eye-witnesses of the Word. <i><mark>Irenaeus looked into the eyes of Polycarp, Polycarp looked into the eyes of John, and John looked into the eyes of Christ.</mark></i> <small> Rev. John Roche Ardill, <a name="JASP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JASP"><cite title="source">St. Patrick A.D. 180</cite></a> ([Dec. 1931]) 173</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Ardill adds that Patrick may have looked into the eyes of Irenaeus. </mm> </dd></dl>
